through close alliances with conceptual and abstract art, performance, photography, film, and new media. To do so, Ledesma draws on pertinent theories of metaphor, affect, time, space, iconicity, and cybernetics. Ledesma shows how José Juan Tablada (Mexico), Joan Salvat-Papasseit (Catalonia), Clemente Padín (Uruguay), Fernando Millán (Spain), Décio Pignatari (Brazil), Ana María Uribe (Argentina), and others turn words, machines, and, more recently, the digital into flesh, making word-objects "come alive" by assembling text to act and seem human, whether on the page, on walls, or on screens.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)xLatin America. 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)zLatin America. 0aExperimental poetry, Latin AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Literature)xLatin AmericaxLatin America. 0aModernism (Literature)zLatin America. 4aArea Studies : Hispanic Studies. 4aArea Studies : Spanish Studies. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Hispanic American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2016z978311149098440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846202840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438462028423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438462028/original  a978-3-11-149098-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles